: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Orange boxes above the=
 dotted line represent the key parties &#8211; obligors (the mortgage borro=
wer), the originator (the lender that created the mortgage), and the invest=
or (the buyer of the pooled mortgages). </span><strong>The core function of=
 the securitization is to aggregate cash from the underlying obligors, divv=
y them up, and distribute the cash to investors.</strong></p><p style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Why d=
o we need 14 service providers to do that? Let&#8217;s dig into the typical=
 monthly flow of funds for a securitization:</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0;=
"><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margi=
n-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Borrower pays:</strong><span> Mortg=
age borrowers send loan payments to an originator or servicer</span></p></l=
i><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margi=
n-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Servicer remits the payment: </stro=
ng><span>Payments are sent to the securitization&#8217;s bank account</span=
></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: =
0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Custodial agents track loan=
 performance: </strong><span>The custodial agent, which &#8220;owns&#8221; =
the loan (PDF loan documents) on behalf of the securitization, allocates ea=
ch dollar to the underlying loan to document ongoing loan performance</span=
></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: =
0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Calculation agents determin=
e payouts:</strong><span> The calculation agent calculates the principal an=
d interest due to each tranche of the securitization</span></p></li><li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4p=
x;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Paying agents pays:</strong><span> The payin=
g agent debits the securitization&#8217;s bank account and wires the dollar=
s due to each tranche to DTCC (a central clearing system that custodies mos=
t public U.S. securitization tranches on behalf of investors)</span></p></l=
i><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margi=
n-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>DTCC distributes the payments: </st=
rong><span>The dollars are sent to custodial agents, which are often prime =
brokers</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; m=
argin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Prime brokers =
pays investors :</strong><span> Prime brokers remit the cash due to investo=
rs in each tranche, depending on their pro-rata ownership share&#160;</span=
></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: =
0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Auditors review everything:=
</strong><span> All transactions are documented by the reporting agent for =
auditors</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; =
margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Trustees aggr=
egate a report:</strong><span> Trustees generate a monthly &#8220;trustee r=
eport,&#8221; which allow investors to track performance and verify payment=
s were made correctly</span></p></li></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Costs are accumula=
ted each step of the way, </span><strong><a href=3D"https://substack.com/re=
direct/dd17dec6-c989-4563-9275-6f077d3c6fd4?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"co=
lor: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">adding an estimated 1% over the =
life of a securitization</a></strong><span>. This might seem small, but </s=
pan><strong>even a 0.50% interest rate reduction on a $500,000 mortgage sav=
es $2,500 per year of post-tax salary</strong><span>, which is a meaningful=
 difference in most people&#8217;s lives! That is a staggering cost for per=
forming simple arithmetic, distributing cash according to a series of &#822=
0;if/then&#8221; statements, and providing an accurate report of transactio=
ns.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Assuming I haven&#8217;t lost you yet, here&#8217;s =
another example. What if I&#8217;m an investor and I want to buy a particul=
ar tranche of securitized debt? Today, the process looks something like thi=
s:</p><ol style=3D"margin-top: 0;"><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-=
left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>In=
stigation:</strong><span> I call up John, my favorite bond trader on Wall S=
treet, and say &#8220;hey, I&#8217;m looking for this particular tranche an=
d willing to pay $Z.&#8221;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px;=
 margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><s=
trong>Sourcing: </strong><span>John calls up a few hedge funds, but no one =
knows who owns the tranche I&#8217;m looking for. One ventures a guess that=
 it&#8217;s Tim, over at Fund A. Luckily, John took Tim out to Lavo last we=
ek, so he gives him a call.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px;=
 margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1=
a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><s=
trong>Getting an offer: </strong><span>After some posturing, Tim finally ac=
knowledges he&#8217;s the owner. John asks him what price he&#8217;s willin=
g to sell his bonds. Tim says &#8220;I&#8217;d sell for $Z.&#8221;</span></=
p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; =
margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>Negotiating the broker&#8217;s=
 spread:</strong><span> &#8220;Just my luck&#8221; says John. There&#8217;s=
 no money in it for him, buying and selling at $Z, so he tries to negotiate=
 a spread for himself in the middle.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin-bot=
tom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px;"><p style=3D"=
color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-botto=
m: 0;"><strong>Final price:</strong><span> Ultimately, I decide I&#8217;m w=
illing to pay no more than $Z and Tim (whose identity John has kept from me=
) would accept no less than $ZX. But whatever, right? There&#8217;s a buyer=
 and a seller at price $Z, so there&#8217;s a trade to do.</span></p></li><=
li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-t=
op: 4px;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><strong>F**k it:</strong><span> Wrong! John de=
cides he&#8217;d rather wait for one of us to budge and refuses to broker t=
he trade for no commission. Because Tim has only exposed his position to Jo=
hn, I have no way of completing a trade that *should* happen.</span></p></l=
i></ol><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>While this seems so obviously stupid, I know this is =
how it works because I was John in a past life. And while stupid can be har=
mless, I believe the compounding inefficiencies that plague our financial i=
ndustry are more nefarious than they appear. In the second example, the ina=
bility to sell one&#8217;s position without going through an oligopoly of W=
all Street brokers contributes to an &#8220;illiquidity premium&#8221; on t=
his debt. That means that, all things equal, investors demand a higher yiel=
d on their mortgage-backed securities. </span><strong>This increases X%, or=
 an originator&#8217;s cost of borrowing, which is transmitted to consumers=
 in the form of higher mortgage rates.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color:=
 #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">It may be=
 controversial to say that we&#8217;ve reached the theoretical limits of ou=
r existing system. But it&#8217;s not controversial to say that our existin=
g system is like Windows XP; I&#8217;m pretty sure that a good portion of t=
he &#8220;tech stack&#8221; on Wall Street is still a macro-enabled 1997 Ex=
cel Workbook. So what would a new operating system for securitized credit l=
ook like? One in which the core first principles - larger scale, more liqui=
dity, and better targeting - were enhanced through new technologies and rem=
oving intermediaries?</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-=
